The '''Minneapolis Arts Commission''' is the [[arts council]] for the city of [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota in the United States. It was established in 1974. The 17 volunteer commissioners are appointed by the mayor and city council. The commission's role includes finding support for the arts from both public and private sources.<ref name=history>{{cite web |title=A Brief History of the Minneapolis Arts Commission |url=http://www.ci.minneapolis.mn.us/dca/mac/dca_art_commission_history |publisher=City of Minneapolis, MN |date=29 January 2010 |accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref>
==History==
In the mid 1970s the Arts Commission looked for a project to provide space for arts activities in an area the city wanted to redevelop economically. They received a grant from the Design Arts program of [[National Endowment for the Arts]] to fund a feasibility study for converting the historic Masonic Temple into an arts center. The result was the opening of the [[Hennepin Center for the Arts]] in 1979.<ref name="Gibans1982">{{cite book |last=Gibans |first=Nina Freedlander |title=The Community Arts Council Movement: History, Opinions, Issues |date=1982 |publisher=Praeger |pages=141–142 |isbn=0-03-062052-X}}</ref>
In 1999 the commission became part of the new Office of Cultural Affairs, along with the Office of Film, Video and New Media.<ref name=history /> In 2002 this new office was cut back significantly by the mayor as part of reducing the city debt.<ref name=Combs2005>{{cite news |last=Combs |first=Marianne |title=Minneapolis unveils new plan for the arts |url=http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/2005/09/22_combsm_mplsartsplan/?refid=0 |publisher=Minnesota Public Radio |date=22 September 2005}}</ref>
In the early 2000s the Arts Commission developed the new Minneapolis 10-year plan for the arts. The ''Minneapolis Plan for Arts and Culture'' was made public in September 2005.<ref name=Combs2005 />
